  "summary": "The narrator expresses a deep sense of foreboding and unease to Franklin. Judith emerges from the house with a serious expression, prompting Norton to compare her to the Jewish heroine who decapitated Holofernes. Judith moves to sit with Franklin, noting that Mrs. Franklin has invited the group to her room for coffee.\n\nThe group gathers in Mrs. Franklin's room, where she prepares coffee with the assistance of Nurse Creven. The attendees include Franklin, Boyd Carlington, Elizabeth Cole, Norton, and the narrator. While the group discusses a crossword puzzle, debating clues regarding Tennyson and Shakespeare, Judith walks out onto the terrace. She calls out that she sees shooting stars, prompting Boyd Carlington to lead most of the group, including Mrs. Franklin, out to the balcony to make wishes.\n\nLeft alone with the newspaper, the narrator becomes overwhelmed by a memory of a tropical night and Cindy, leading to silent tears. To hide his distress from Judith when she re-enters, he pretends to study a book of Shakespeare. After the group disperses, Franklin expresses satisfaction with his evening and goes for a walk. The narrator later encounters Franklin and Judith in the hallway; Franklin asks Judith to walk with him, but she declines. After the narrator parts ways with Franklin, he goes to Bello's room and finds Judith. She kisses him and asks for his forgiveness regarding an incident involving \"Uncle Heracles.\"",
